what is centrality
For each CUI in a semantic type, we compute:
centrality(C) = -log(reach(C) / total_in_type)
Where:

reach(C) = how many CUIs in the same semantic type are reachable from C through allowed relations
total_in_type = total CUIs in that semantic type

Examples (made up but realistic for finding semantic type with say 50,000 CUIs):
CUIReachReach / TotalCentralityPain30,0000.60-log(0.60) = 0.51Lower limb pain5,0000.10-log(0.10) = 2.30Knee pain5000.01-log(0.01) = 4.61Left knee pain500.001-log(0.001) = 6.91
Higher centrality = more specific/peripheral. Lower centrality = more general/central in the graph.
Now the BFS bound
When we BFS-expand from a source CUI, we set:
threshold = source_centrality - 0.5
Then we ONLY walk to a neighbor if neighbor_centrality >= threshold.
In other words: we refuse to walk to a CUI whose centrality is more than 0.5 below the source's.
Concrete example: starting from "Knee pain"

Source: Knee pain, centrality = 4.61
Threshold = 4.61 − 0.5 = 4.11
BFS will accept neighbors with centrality ≥ 4.11
BFS will REJECT neighbors with centrality < 4.11

